[normal]We represented Mr Moha
[normal]med as his solicitors following his arrival in the UK on 14 March 2011, after he had been removed against his will from Somaliland to the UK (as opposed to Somalia where he lived with his wife and child) and was upon arrival placed under a Control Order and required to live in Ipswich.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A number of legal challenges came to be made on Mr Mohamed's behalf. All of these have far wider significance than for his case alone. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The central issues on which the courts had to decide were
[normal]:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1
[normal]. 
[normal]The legality of the Control Order imposed on 'CC' at the airport when he arrived in the UK on 14 March 2011.
[normal]2. The subsequent legality of the TPIM (Control Orders having given way to
[normal] 
[normal]TPIMs in January 2012). (The challenges to these two orders were
[normal] 
[normal]conjoined in proceedings in the High Court.)
[normal]3. The lawfulness of the Schedule 7 examination of CC at Heathrow Airport.
[normal]4. The evidence that supported an allegation of "tampering" with the G4S/GPS
[normal] 
[normal]tag worn by him between 19th April and 16th May 2013.
[normal]5. The sequence of the allegations of breaches of the Control Order and the
[normal] 
[normal]TPIM and their treatment by the courts.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We start with the period of time in which Mr Mohamed was imprisoned for breaches of
[normal] 
[normal]obligations placed upon him by first the Control Order and then the TPIM.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The sequence of the allegations of breaches of the Control Order and the TPIM and their treatment by the courts.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Mr Moha
[normal]med was arrested, as the evidence given to your Committee by Charles Farr
[normal] 
[normal]correctly stated, for breaches of the Control Order between August and October 2011.
[normal] 
[normal](Thereafter he was charged with breaches of the TPIM.) The evidence on this issue
[normal] 
