[normal]The comments we would make are these;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]a) Mr Moha
[normal]med, remanded in custody for the 14 and 6 breaches, had at
[normal] 
[normal]the time of his respective releases on bail, already served over 8 months
[normal] 
[normal]on remand in prison. It had already been acknowledged by the
[normal] 
[normal]prosecution by the time of his release on 6th August 2013 for the third
[normal] 
[normal]"tamper" allegation, that even if he had been convicted of the previous
[normal] 
[normal]breaches at a subsequent trial, he would have already served more than
[normal] 
[normal]his sentence for those breaches by reason of the time he 
[normal]had already spent in prison
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]b) The context of the 14 and 6 breaches was this; Mr Mohamed had been
[normal] 
[normal]seized in what later emerged as a joint "operation" with UK agencies by
[normal] 
[normal]forces in Somaliland. The description he subsequently gave was of
[normal] 
[normal]severe ill treatment for two months by Somaliland officers including
[normal] 
[normal]treatment categorised as constituting torture for two months 
[normal]–
[normal] the
[normal] 
[normal]questions put to him while detained focussed on information relevant to
[normal] 
[normal]the UK. At the conclusion of his detention in Somaliland, instead of being
[normal] 
[normal]returned as he had asked to Somalia where he had resided for many
[normal] 
[normal]years with his wife and child, he was forcibly removed to the UK.
[normal] 
[normal]Immediately on arrival he was placed under a Control Order and required
[normal] 
[normal]to live in Ipswich where he knew nobody. He was not only traumatised
[normal] 
[normal]from his experience beginning on 14th January 2011 (of which medical
[normal] 
[normal]evidence was available to the courts) but was entirely isolated in Ipswich.
[normal] 
[normal]For that reason and others, a number of the severe regulations upon him,
[normal] 
[normal]imposed by the Control Order were breached by him. At the time of his
[normal] 
[normal]arrest, for a second set of breaches, he commented that he preferred to
[normal] 
[normal]be in prison, as at least he would be with other people.
